Barack Obama Receives Nobel Peace Prize as Fourth President of the United States
U.S. President Barack Obama is coming to Oslo, Norway for 26 hours to win the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth U.S. President in history.
In addition, he receives the diploma as well as the medal and a cheque of $1.4 million for his extraordinary efforts to intensify world diplomacy and cooperation among peoples.
The head of the White House arrives tomorrow with his wife Michelle in the Nordic metropolis and will be busy all the time.
First, he visits the Nobel Institute, where he meets for the first time ever with the five committee members who elected him in October from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The presidential couple then scheduled a meeting with Norwegian King Harald V and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit reaches its climax with the ceremony, in which Obama takes over the prestige prize.
He is the fourth President of the United States, but only the third to receive the prize directly in office.
The White House has already said that Obama will talk about the Afghanistan War when he takes over the prize.
The president does not want to dodge this issue because he knows he is taking over the prize as a president who is currently waging war in two countries.
He reinforced the war effort a few days ago by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics forget to highlight.
At the ceremony, Obama also received the gold medal, diploma and check over ten million Swedish crowns (approximately 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to donate the money for charitable purposes, but he has not yet decided on a specific charitable work.
The event programme then includes a banquet with the President and his wife, where, in addition to Norway’s King and Queen, the Prime Minister and another 250 invited guests will also be present.
Obama has been very cautious about the price from the beginning.
For example, he stated that he felt that he did not quite deserve the prize.
He also repeated several times that it is not just the price for him, but for all those who seek the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he stated that this was for him "invitation to action".
