The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds to prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the organism.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works with the viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact outweighs the disadvantage that the compound does not work as strongly on common virus variants as one of the already existing drugs.
AIDS cannot be cured yet.
However, patients can prolong the drug composition and prevent the proliferation of HIV viruses in the body.
However, your intake is accompanied by a number of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of the virus propagation also leads to the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which no more drugs are effective.
The work of the experts of three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, of the VSCHT (Chemical-Technological University of Prague) and of the University of Heidelberg opens the way to dealing with virus resistance.
They have shown that the substances called metalocarboranes act on the protein that is responsible for proliferation of the HIV virus.
The metalocarboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block virus propagation in a different way than all medicines used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists arrive at new 'improved' compounds prepared on the basis of the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus protein.
The metalocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multifaceted cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Insidious and resistant virus
HIV protease is the protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV-protease-induced splitting of the HIV virus, no mature infectious virus particles would arise.
When we turn off HIV protease, we also turn off the propagation of the virus in the patient’s body, the scientists explain in the press report published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the paper published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe whole series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically modified further.
A little weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances against HIV protease was tested in the test tube, including against their resistant (resistant) variants obtained from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of metalocarboranes on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as in the case of clinically used medicinal products, but it does not lose its effect on the resistant variants against which the medicinal products used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action, as well as its other properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical formation, makes the metalocarborans interesting compounds for further research aimed at the development of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlina Rezacova, head of the Laboratory of Structural Biology of the Institutes of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
