Vaccination against pneumococcal free and voluntary
Vaccination against pneumococcal changes habits from January onwards.
It should be the first to be free and voluntary for families.
But already now voices are reporting that compulsory vaccination would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of the free vaccination against pneumococcal culminate.
The Pharmaceutical Institute already sets the maximum prices of vaccines that the health insurance companies have to pay.
The experts are also aware of the vaccination procedure.
New vaccination
Vaccines free for August children
As of January, children can be vaccinated free of charge against pneumococci born on August 2 last year and later.
The condition is that they have not received a vaccine dose yet.
Anyone who has already started vaccination in the last year or earlier, must also pay for further revaccination themselves.
The first dose of vaccine must be given between the 3rd and 5th month of life of the child.
Last year, a quarter of families had their children vaccinated against pneumococci.
The parents paid 1,600 crowns and more for a dose.
Four doses are required for the vaccination of the youngest children.
Overall, the experts estimate that the health insurances for vaccine doses spend 300,000 to 450,000 crowns per year.
However, they save on the treatment that the children would need without vaccination.
So far, the state has spent about 500,000 per year on all children’s land vaccinations.
The compulsory vaccination was introduced with the so-called Janota package.
Pneumococcal causes middle ear infection, but also severe infections including brain skin inflammation and blood poisoning.
As a result of pneumococcal infections, up to 28 children up to 10 years old die in hospitals every year.
Outside the Czech Republic, the compulsory vaccination of children against pneumococci was introduced in about 40 countries.
Will vaccination be mandatory?
At the same time, it is said that this vaccination could be mandatory in the future.
From January, it will be paid by the insurance companies and will be voluntary.
That the compulsory vaccination would be better, mentioned, for example, the head of the citizen association Nahlas, Rudolf Kalovsky.
His association has been promoting pneumococcal vaccination in the long term.
The experts at the international conference in which our association was involved were not very satisfied with the fact that we have voluntary vaccination.
That's not quite ideal.
On the other hand, we are glad that we have managed to achieve at least that.
I think that's the way we have to go now, Kalovsky said.
However, the Ministry of Health does not want to change the vaccination procedure against pneumococcal disease.
At this moment we are not considering this at all, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sesen.
Voluntary vaccination has its disadvantages, the doctors claim.
Hana Cabrnochova, chairman of the Society of Practical Pediatricians, admits that voluntary vaccination has its disadvantages.
“In a situation where the vaccine is so expensive, we understand the political decision that this vaccination has been started as a voluntary one,” Cabrnochova says.
Experts expect more than 80 percent of parents to have their infants vaccinated against pneumococcal from next year.
Vaccination against pneumococcal is also groundbreaking in the fact that it is the first area vaccination paid by the health insurance companies and not by the state.
“Insurers should spend the money on prevention so they can save for further treatment,” Cabrnochova said.
Doctors need to buy the vaccines themselves.
However, this is associated with a concern of practical pediatricians concerning the purchase of vaccines.
According to the original plan, the vaccines should be purchased by the insurance companies and the doctors then receive them in the same way as other vaccines issued by the state to them.
