The average birth rate has fallen to 1.8 children per couple compared to 6 at the time that this policy came into force, according to the UN.
The Department of Population Affairs is set to increase explosively from 16.7 per cent of the population by 2050 to 31.1 per cent in 2020, well above the global average of about 20 per cent.
The imbalance is stronger in rich coastal cities with educated populations, such as Shanghai.
Last year, 60-year-olds and older people accounted for almost 22 percent of Shanghai’s reported residents, while the birth rate was below one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, head of the Shanghai City Population and Family Planning Commission, has said that couples must have babies of procreative age to “help reduce the ratio of ageing populations and alleviate the labour shortages of the future.”
Shanghai will soon be "as old -- but not as rich -- as the developed countries, such as Japan and Sweden," she said.
A gradual relaxation
Enshrined in the country’s constitution in 1978, China’s one-child policy is likely to be the most controversial order introduced by the ruling Communist Party to this day.
Couples who violate this policy face enormous fines -- up to three times their annual salary in some regions -- and discrimination in their workplaces.
Chinese officials attributed it to this policy that the critical use of the natural resources of the country could be avoided, whereas human rights officials have condemned abuses in the enforcement of the policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who already had a child to abort.
Many couples had also had sex-selective abortions performed, resulting in an unnaturally high ratio of men to women.
In recent years, government officials for the population have gradually weakened their stance on one-child policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including city dwellers, members of ethnic minorities, and cases where both husband and wife were single children -- and in 2007, the tone of many harsh slogans was mitigated.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at Beijing University’s Institute of Population Research, said that government officials have recently discussed even more radical changes, for example, allowing couples to have two children in which a partner is a single child.
Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births in July.
Posters that taught families to have only one child were replaced almost overnight by guidelines that describe in detail who is eligible for a second child and how to apply for approval.
The city administration has sent out city employees and volunteers for family planning to visit couples at home and push through information sheets under the doors.
She also asked to provide psychological and financial advice for those who have more than one child.
The response was not exactly encouraging, family planning officials said.
Disappointing reaction
Although officials from a rural small town in the outskirts of Shanghai said that there is a surge in requests from couples who want a second child after the start of the campaign, the urban districts do not report any change.
The municipality of Huinan with a population of 115,000 still receives as an example only four to five applications per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say the expected number of births in the city for 2010 will still be around 165,000 despite the campaign -- slightly higher than 2009, but lower than 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee of the Shanghai community of Caolu, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people don’t want to have more children.
They want to give the best to their first, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said that they would like to have two children and this is legally permitted.
But they, like many Chinese, have only a small amount of government health and life insurance.
Without a social network, they say, this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West falsely rate the one-child policy as a human rights issue, said Yang, a civil engineer whose wife is pregnant with her first child in the seventh month.
Yes, we are deprived of the possibility of having more than one child.
But the problem is not just in politics.
The problem is money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the human resources manager, said she only wanted a child because she was also a single child. "We were the center of the family and used to have everyone take care of us.
We’re not used to caring for others and we don’t really want to.”
Chen Zijian, a 42-year-old who owns a translation company, said it bluntly.
For middle-sized parents with a double career, which lowers the birth rate, he said, it’s about being successful and for that you have to be selfish.
The age group of today’s 20- to 39-year-olds grew up to see their parents struggling during the early days of the Chinese capitalism experiment and they don’t want such a life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child, he said, places huge demands on parents’ time.
A mother must give up her social life for at least two years.
Then there is the space question -- "You have to rebuild your apartment" -- and the life plan -- "When the child is 9 months old, you already have to have a resume for the best preschools."
