The UN-sponsored climate conference -- which has so far been characterised by wild poses and mutual accusations -- re-focused on Friday with the publication of a document that records an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases for the next 40 years, with the industrial nations having to shoulder the greatest burden in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a definitive political agreement on the regulation of greenhouse gases, showed both the remaining obstacles and the way forward.
But he was seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that is running out of time as more than 100 top politicians from all over the world will arrive in Copenhagen next week.
The text, formulated by a UN working group created specifically for this purpose, is silent about the money supply that rich countries should give to poor countries so that they can cope with global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options for key issues, including how industrialized and large emerging economies can limit their carbon emissions and how high the upper limit of global temperature rise should be that policymakers would contribute.
The process is given a great deal of flexibility, according to John Coequyt, senior representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who designed the six-page document, has summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN’s leading climate protection representative, Yvo de Boer, has described as “the big picture.”
It shows the ground plan of a possible agreement in which industrial nations would jointly reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to the 1990 limit values, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent over the same period.
Together, the countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community has also boosted the talks on Friday by promising to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the impacts of climate change – from mastering floods and droughts to avoiding deforestation.
The Friday still brought the same verbal fireworks that had determined the conversations last week.
U.S. Special Representative for Climate Change Todd Stern has rejected formulations calling for binding reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for industrialized countries, compared to voluntary reductions for larger emerging economies, unless these are financed by the industrialized nations.
This train announced that the Obama administration is running a harder line with China than Bush administration representatives did not even two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without larger emerging economies getting up and taking action, according to Stern, who also complained that the text did not go far enough to ensure that the reductions could also be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern issued his statement one hour after China’s Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei said that the leading American climate negotiator either lacked “reason” or was “very irresponsible” of saying earlier this week that the United States would not financially help China master global warming.
Because the future economic direction of the great world powers is at stake, breaking lines have opened up within the industrialized nations as well as between the industrialized nations and the emerging economies.
The current struggle relates equally to the rescue of individual economies, as well as to the rescue of the planet, with China and the United States advocating for their corresponding commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take bolder action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it is not surprising that the great powers are fighting over who should bear the cost of slowing down greenhouse gas emissions, as even affected countries have gone on to act more aggressively in bringing the countries with very high greenhouse gas emissions to account for their actions.
