Some of the countries most exposed to the effects of climate change stated that they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although the leading participants say that the talks will at best lead to a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States with 43 members submitted a 24-page draft treaty early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said that the small island states' offensive "exerts political pressure on the entire political process," partly because they are now united and demand action from emerging countries, such as China and India.
The talks received a new urgency as the delegates focused on the fact that most of the open issues must be clarified before the arrival of the leaders in order to reach an agreement.
High-ranking representatives, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Vice Minister, boarded their planes and rushed through the corridors of the Bella Center to meetings behind closed doors and press conferences to set out claims to be negotiated during the next week.
The sheer extent of the assembly -- 13,000 people go in and out of the convention center every day, guitar-playing activists host nightly shows in which they make fun of the countries they think are betraying and selling, and draft contracts are hand-to-hand rather than emailed -- is already a challenge.
