The Cradle of Dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: the two-metre-long and 1.50-metre-large animal ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would be nothing special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs to have these body features, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in Thursday’s journal Science.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in present-day New Mexico, which was then in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangea on the equator.
Tawa opens a new window to the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
He shows us a lot about the relationship, the spread, and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavating at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Triassic, reports team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as a new species.
In the course of the excavation, they carried the remains of a total of five individuals together.
Find confirms theories about dino early history
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an extraordinary find: "Dinosaurus fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare, usually you can only find individual fragments."
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This find is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current doctrine, the dinosaurs appeared for the first time about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the allocation of these original dinosaurs is usually controversial.
The experts debate, for example, when the lizards split into their three main lines of development: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the tyrannosaurus rex, the velociraptor and also the birds known as the "long-necked sauropods" and their relatives, and the plant-eating ornithologists, for example, the ornithologists.
After analyzing Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropode.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found clues to airbags, as they also possess the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the airbags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
At Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with airbags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of the giant sauropods later also had airbags and lightweight bones, probably the common ancestor of both groups had already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, the researchers conclude that the lizards appeared there for the first time.
Accordingly, the three development lines separated early and spread from South America across all continents, which at that time still formed a single land mass as the supercontinent Pangea.
The fact speaks for this is that the team, together with Tawa hallae, found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods.
The three cannot descend from a common, immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
In his opinion, there could be a distorted picture, because in South America there are just a lot of primitive Dino fossils preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to be found.
How the dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare sideline of the reptile tribe to the dominant land vertebrates of the Earth’s Middle Ages is still enigmatic.
During the Triassic, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example, with the ancestors of today’s crocodiles and aeronauts and with numerous other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread all over the world and developed many new species, while relatives on the border from the Triassic to the Jura died out.
Success story did not last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so that they could beat the competition out of the field.
In any case, the success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact of a group of animals helped to bloom, which had also developed in the Triassic and since then a shadow existence has been frosting: the mammals.
