Unlike in the dream, Fuchs says, "but the sensual and spatial structure of reality, which is perceived in psychosis, remains fundamentally preserved."
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based in reality, the alienation of the experience takes place in the real context.
Why exactly our brain beats caprioles, researchers are still posing puzzles.
Exceptional states can cause any person to lose the reference to reality for a short time, says Fuchs.
But not everyone will develop a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that the genes are not the sole determining factors.
Researchers assume that there is minimal brain damage in those affected.
We suspect that neuronal maturation of the brain is disrupted at an early stage of development, for example, by a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But it remains a mystery how the disturbance of the neural system comes about, which is not manifested at all for many years at first.
Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can trigger a psychosis if the disposition is present.
Even hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychosis as they interfere with the transmitter system.
When our brains are hot
The crazy thing is, psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and swallow expensive drugs to get rid of them, others spend money on drugs to get some, says Lübeck psychology professor Erich Kasten.
Whether deceptions are perceived as pleasant or unpleasant is often only a matter of point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports of hallucinations and delusions for ten years, last year he evaluated his results in the book "The Irral World in Our Head".
Hallucinations are among the typical concomitant symptoms of psychosis, but also of surprisingly many other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline or depression, these often include diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer’s and cranial brain trauma.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, even the brains of healthy people hallucinate.
Hallucinations, according to castes, are composed of memory contents that are usually withheld.
They arise when brain areas in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or insufficiently inhibited; when our brain is running hot or even when stimulation is lacking.
Drugs can trigger this condition just as much as brain damage or psychosis.
But also irritation deprivation, stress, love grief or other mental exceptional states.
In recent studies, up to one-third of respondents reported having experienced hallucination at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005 Sarah K. is 16 years old, she lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and visits the high school there.
A normal girl, actually.
If not the pictures and voices.
During the break, a sluggish boy with long, dark hair may respond to it.
When it answers him, the classmates look at it surprisingly - no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think the shy girl is a spun daydreamer, but Sarah K. doesn’t dream, she knows.
She is awake, she hears and sees this boy, just as she hears and sees the girl in the bench next to her.
She can even feel his presence, at least for moments.
A pleasant feeling is that she likes the boy.
Am I crazy? she asks herself sometimes.
But she knows that this boy and the other delusions are not real and disappear again.
At night, the apparitions are usually scary.
Often, the deceptions are also a burden.
When she sits in the classroom, she can sometimes not follow the teaching material because the teacher is presenting a new classmate in her eyes and ears, while explaining mathematical equations to all others in audible and visible manner at the table.
At night, the apparitions are usually scary.
If she waits in her dark room for sleep, which is far too rare and far too late, she often cannot tell whether she is awake or already dreaming, whether the pictures she sees, the fractures or the girl with the bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, arise in front of her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, she screams at the figures.
Parents and friends don’t tell them that they think they’re crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She passed high school last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Since she made contact with the psychologist Kasten on the Internet, she knows exactly that she is not crazy.
Delusion is also a work of art of despair
If someone is socially isolated or suffers from irritation deprivation, he is likely to have hallucinations after a while, says Kasten.
I suspect the brain is then underused and takes care of its own entertainment.
Sarah K., a single child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at the age of 13 that the man she calls daddy has not been her biological father since she can think.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations have the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and noises, it is difficult for those affected, such as Sarah K., to distinguish falsehoods and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "is taking place in the brain, the reality is formed there.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain creates, which is why they look so real.”
Even nocturnal dream images value caste as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their delusions as irreversible.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to appreciate the hallucinations as a special ability.
Border state between dream and hallucination
Unfortunately, in our very conscious world, imaginary experiences are usually pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Department of Psychiatry and Psychotherapy at the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful illness, but it also contains positive, creative - delusion is also a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has explored the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of traumatically altered awakening consciousness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams, which the person experiencing considers to be real and which he cannot distinguish from the waking state even in hindsight.
The one-iroid state of consciousness arises in trauma- or disease-related extreme situations, for example in polyradiculitis patients who experience motor paralysis when fully conscious.
When a person is threatened with self- and world loss, for example by sustained, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own imaginary world, which is decoupled from reality, Schmidt-Degenhard says.
A kind of borderline state between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to cope with a situation in reality, a world change takes place, but the real situation is reflected in the imagination.
An intense form of the foundation of meaning and meaning in a situation that is intrinsically intolerable, which enables us to create our own capacity, not to perish in a nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his oneiroid experiences in his book "Heart Change" as a rescue action of the soul.
He is 49 years old when his consciousness travels for days after a heart valve surgery followed by a heart transplant, while his body is doomed to motionlessness in the intensive care unit.
Claussen dives into a self-created world, visits foreign times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden, old man, aboard a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among nobles who produce intoxicants from blood.
When transported by a Greek on a motorcycle to his home country, he surfs with his hospital bed in the firn snow of the Alps and meets a Korean mafioso.
It goes up completely in the imaginary event, everything is real, even later in memory.
These inner journeys are fundamentally different for Claussen from any dream.
Dream is a different state, he describes his experience.
In contrast, the memories from mental journeys are still clear to me after years and in minor details.
Clearer and more intense than really experienced.
The intensity of this experience blows the horizon of our other life-world experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
In the end, oneiroids, psychosis, hallucinations and drug rush show how fragile our inner images of external reality are also in the wake.
Any change in the state of consciousness, the psychologist Kasten sums up, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be enriching.
