Support for braking manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As with the ABS anti-lock braking system back then and as with the stability control ESP, the auxiliary systems for braking in emergencies must become a mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly registered passenger cars and light vans, for the remaining vehicles a deferral period was set until the end of February 2011.
The action adopted by the European Union aims to improve the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many rear-end accidents due to their way of working.
The task of the emergency brake assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the case of a critical braking maneuver, which the system detects on the brake pedal based on the braking strength executed by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident were no longer able to step on the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not braked with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The braking aid, on the other hand, engages with maximum force in the braking system and thereby reduces the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car travels during the braking process.
According to a study by the EU, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assist.
There would be even fewer accidents - one in four accidents with personal injury could be prevented - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while exerting a slight pressure on the brakes at the same time.
If the driver reacts, the system helps him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already inevitable, the brake assistant exerts maximum pressure on the brakes in order to keep the damage as low as possible.
